# Environment Variables Configuration
# Clinic Portal Application

# =============================================================================
# DATABASE CONFIGURATION (REQUIRED)
# =============================================================================

# Turso Database Connection URL
# This is the primary connection string for your Turso database instance
# Format: libsql://[database-name]-[organization].turso.io
# Where to get: Create a database at https://turso.tech/ and copy the URL from your dashboard
TURSO_CONNECTION_URL=libsql://your-database-name-your-org.turso.io

# Turso Database Authentication Token
# This token authenticates your application with the Turso database
# Format: Alphanumeric string (usually starts with "eyJ...")
# Where to get: Generate from Turso dashboard > Database > Settings > Tokens
# Security: Keep this secret and never commit to version control
TURSO_AUTH_TOKEN=eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9...your-auth-token-here

# =============================================================================
# AUTHENTICATION CONFIGURATION (RECOMMENDED)
# =============================================================================

# JWT Secret Key for Token Signing
# Used to sign and verify JWT tokens for user authentication
# Format: Random string (minimum 32 characters recommended)
# Generate: Use `openssl rand -base64 32` or any secure random string generator
# Security: Use a strong, unique secret for production environments
# Note: Application will work without this but uses a default fallback (not recommended for production)
JWT_SECRET=your-super-secure-jwt-secret-key-at-least-32-characters-long

# =============================================================================
# DEVELOPMENT NOTES
# =============================================================================

# 1. Copy this file to .env.local for local development
# 2. Never commit .env.local or any file containing real secrets to git
# 3. For production deployment, set these variables in your hosting platform's environment settings
# 4. Ensure .env.local is listed in your .gitignore file

# =============================================================================
# SECURITY RECOMMENDATIONS
# =============================================================================

# ✅ DO:
# - Use strong, unique values for all secrets
# - Rotate tokens regularly
# - Use different values for development/staging/production environments
# - Set environment variables through your hosting platform's dashboard

# ❌ DON'T:
# - Use the same secrets across multiple environments
# - Commit real environment variables to version control
# - Share these values in plain text communications
# - Use weak or predictable secret keys